able&#x000a0;<xref ref-type="table" rid="T5">5</xref>).</p><p>In order to assess the effects of weight loss on liver function parameters patients were stratified according to degree of weight loss (weight gain, 1-5% weight loss, 5-10% weight loss, and more than 10% weight loss). Both diets proved to be efficacious in the improvement of liver function parameters.</p></sec><sec><title>In NGLCD patients group</title><p>In patients with less than 5% loss of baseline weight (n&#x02009;=&#x02009;30) (&#x02212;2.1 kg [95% CI &#x02212;2.5, -1.75]) there was an improvement of ALT levels (&#x02212;15.1 [95% CI &#x02212;22.8, - 7.5]), GGT levels (&#x02212;6.4 [95% CI [&#x02212;10.9, -1.9]), AST/ALT ratio (&#x02212;0.07 [95% CI, -0.002, -0.14]) and Forns index (&#x02212;0.17 [(95% CI, -0.005, -0.28]) (Table&#x000a0;<xref ref-type="table" rid="T6">6</xref>).</p><table-wrap position="float" id="T6"><label>Table 6</label><caption><p>Groups of weight loss and liver function parameters in patients with NGLCD</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups" border="1"><colgroup><col align="left"/><col align="left"/><col align="left"/><col align="left"/><col align="left"/><col align="left"/><col align="left"/><col align="left"/><col align="left"/><col align="left"/><col align="left"/></colgroup><thead valign="top"><tr><th align="left" valign="bottom">&#x000a0;<hr/></th><th align="left" valign="bottom">&#x000a0;<hr/></th><th colspan="2" align="left" valign="bottom"><bold>Weight gain</bold><hr/></th><th colspan="2" align="left" valign="bottom"><bold>1-5% weight loss</bold><hr/></th><th colspan="2" align="left" valign="bottom"><bold>5-10% weight loss</bold><hr/></th><th colspan="2" align="left" valign="bottom"><bold>Weight loss &#x0003e;10%</bold><hr/></th><th align="left" valign="bottom"><bold>p</bold><hr/></th></tr><tr><th align="left">&#x000a0;</th><th align="left">&#x000a0;</th><th align="left"><bold>Mean</bold></th><th align="left"><bold>SD</bold></th><th align="left"><bold>Mean</b